My own feeling- l will not say conviction-is that, if Virgil is to be interpreted by his own poemS, the evidence a priori is overwhelming that the new age and the hopes of Italy could only be personified* by him asa member of the family oi the Caesars. Pollio, Varus, Gallus are helpful human friends in these early poems, and then disappear5 but Augustus is ever in Virgil's mind from the First Eclogue onwards‚ not merely as a human friend and helper, but as the son of the divine JuliuS, and as the pacificator and regenerator of the world. Well indeed might the child of such a man -a man himself not far from the gods-be hailed in the lofty language of our poem.¹
